  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen up close while working with students in Bari. As an electrician with a vocational diploma, I've noticed how kids from my community, especially those who don't see themselves as 'tech people,' start doubting their abilities when they're in classrooms or workshops. My dad had a PhD, but my mom never finished high school, and that gap shapes how some of my own kids view their potential in science. Stereotype threat happens when someone internalizes the belief that they're not good at something because of their group identity—like girls thinking they can't do math or Black students fearing they'll fail in physics. It's real, and it's hurting kids who could be great engineers or scientists. We should address it, but not with lectures or big gestures. Real change starts with small, consistent actions: teachers who know your background and can say, 'I've been there too,' or parents who encourage your curiosity without judgment. I've seen it in my own life—my depression makes me overthink how I'll be perceived, especially when I'm not confident in my technical skills. So yes, we must act. But it's not about fixing people; it's about creating spaces where everyone feels they belong. That means listening more, speaking up when you see bias, and making sure every kid knows they're valued, not just as a 'student' but as a person with potential.",
